{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646627"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:33:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:33:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18193"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18193"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77511"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10907"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18193"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63023"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25358"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25359"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77511"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following stages of intervertebral disc herniation is characterised by the nucleus pulposus lying outside the disc in the spinal canal?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Protrusion","Extrusion","Sequestration","Degeneration","Bulging"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe stage of intervertebral disc herniation where the \u003Cstrong\u003Enucleus pulposus lies outside the disc in the spinal canal\u003C/strong\u003E is known as sequestration. This occurs when the disc material has completely broken through the annulus fibrosus and is free within the spinal canal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtrusion\u003C/strong\u003E - The disc bulges but the nucleus pulposus remains contained within the annulus fibrosus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtrusion\u003C/strong\u003E - The nucleus pulposus herniates through the annulus fibrosus but remains connected to the disc\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDegeneration\u003C/strong\u003E - Refers to the general wear and tear of the disc, not a specific stage of herniation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBulging\u003C/strong\u003E - Similar to protrusion, where the disc extends beyond its normal boundary but the nucleus is contained\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESequestration can lead to significant nerve compression and may require surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intervertebral disc herniation progresses through stages: protrusion, extrusion, and sequestration.","Sequestration is the stage where the nucleus pulposus lies outside the disc in the spinal canal.","Sequestered disc fragments can cause nerve compression and require medical intervention."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/","Dydyk AM, Ngnitewe Massa R, Mesfin FB. Disc Herniation. 2023 Jan 16. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722852."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63023"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18193"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63023"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T10:43:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T10:43:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10907"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77511"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","posi